{"actual_usd":0.12487,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":169,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24467,"reply":"\"No— I don't think that's right.\" *I wipe a little flour from the heel of my hand onto my apron and glance toward the oven, where the heat keeps pressing at my cheek.* \"The resurrection matters terribly, but the cross isn't just the sad part before the victory. It's where He actually gave Himself for us. If you make the cross only suffering, you hollow it out; if you leave out the resurrection, you leave the loaf in the oven and never set it on the table.\"\n\n*I twirl that gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"I'd say they belong together, but not as the same thing. The cross is atonement accomplished; the resurrection is God's vindication of Christ and the public defeat of death. What made you bring it up— somebody arguing it that way?\"","rolling_24h_usd":50.70258000000005,"run_id":"be80a308-8957-477e-8c24-bf6823d4c70c"}
